An '''additur''' ([[Latin]]: "it is added to") is a [[legal term]] referring to the practice of a [[trial]] [[judge]] adding damages additional to the original amount awarded by the [[jury]]. It is not allowed in [[U.S. federal courts]], as held by ''Dimick vs. Schiedt'', 293 U.S. 474 (1935).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://laws.findlaw.com/us/293/474.html |title=Dimick v. Scheidt, 293 U.S. 474 (1935) |publisher=FindLaw |accessdate=2009-03-17}}</ref> However, ''Dimick'' was decided before ''[[Erie Railroad Co. v. Tompkins]]'' (1938), which given the rarity of additur makes it unclear whether federal courts are bound by this rule when [[Erie doctrine|applying state law]] in [[diversity jurisdiction|diversity cases]].
Some [[United States|American states]], on the other hand, allow the practice, including [[California]] and [[New Jersey]].<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Fisch v. Manger |vol=130 |reporter=A.2d |opinion=815| pinpoint= |court=[[Supreme Court of New Jersey|N.J.]] |date=1957 |url= https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?q=130+A.2d+815&hl=en&as_sdt=4,31&case=4747242872667267769&scilh=0accessdate= |quote=}}</ref> It is the opposite of [[remittitur]], which is allowed in federal law. Although this is a rarely used procedure, it is usually granted for punitive damages when it is used in state courts.
